MS subjects produced significantly higher levels of IL-12 in response to PHA/PMA stimulation than did control subjects (M = 64.73 pg/mL, standard error of the mean [SEM] = 23.79 vs. M = 9.70 pg/mL, SEM = 2.28, respectively; U = 14.0, z = −2.63, p = .009). Figure 1
 illustrates the magnitude of this difference. There was also a significant difference in production of IFN-γ (see Figure 2
) as induced by PHA/PMA (U = 165, z = −2.69, p = .007), with MS subjects producing lower amounts in response to stimulation (M = 8.72 ng/mL, SEM = 1.76) than did the control subjects (M = 14.68 ng/mL, SEM = 2.35). While it was not a significant difference, MS subjects tended to produce higher levels of IL-6 (see Figure 3
) in response to both PHA/PMA (M = 24.61 ng/mL, SEM = 2.73) and LPS stimulation (M = 38.20 ng/mL, SEM = 2.18) than control subjects (PHA M = 20.8 ng/mL, SEM = 2.72 and LPS M = 34.75 ng/mL, SEM = 7.63, respectively).
